SIMPLE: eloign
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eloign
<hw>E*loign"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Eloigned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Eloigning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧loigner</ets>, OF. <ets>esloignier</ets>; pref.
<ets>es-</ets> (L. <ets>ex</ets>) + OF. & F. <ets>loin</ets> far, far
off, L. <ets>longe</ets>, fr. <ets>longus</ets> long. See
<er>Elongate</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>eloin</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To remove afar off; to
withdraw.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From worldly cares he did himself <qex>eloign</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To convey to a distance, or beyond
the jurisdiction, or to conceal, as goods liable to distress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sheriff may return that the goods or beasts are
<qex>eloigned</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eloignate</ent>⟦br⟧
